3. WATER ACQUISITION & MANAGEMENT SYSTEM

3.1 In-Situ Resource Utilization (ISRU): Ice Mining

Primary Source: Subsurface glacial ice deposits at 30–60° latitudes
Technology: Rodriguez Well (Rodwell) System

```
Process Flow:
1. Thermal probe deployment to 10m depth
2. Subsurface cavity melting (5–10m diameter bulb)
3. Pumping (submersible, 100 L/min capacity)
4. Filtration (0.2µm ceramic membranes)
5. Storage (insulated, pressurized tanks)
```

· Daily capacity: 1,000–5,000 L per well
· Energy requirement: 2 kW continuous during melting phase
· Redundancy: Minimum 3 wells per settlement

Secondary Source: Atmospheric Water Harvesters (AWH)

· Principle: Temperature-swing adsorption using MOF-801
· Capacity: 0.2–0.5 L/kg-adsorbent per sol
· Deployment: Surface arrays + habitat vent capture
· Emergency role: 30-day survival water during dust storms

3.2 Deuterium Mitigation Strategy

Challenge: Martian water contains ~5× Earth's deuterium concentration (8–10‰ vs 1.5‰)
Biological Impacts:

· Kinetic isotope effect: Slows enzymatic reactions 2–5×
· Growth inhibition: Particularly in seedlings and microbes
· Metabolic drift: Cumulative effects over generations

Mitigation Systems:

```
System                    Application           D₂O Reduction   Energy Cost
------                    -----------           --------------  -----------
Fractional distillation   Starter Culture       90%             500 Wh/L
Membrane separation       Hydroponic reservoirs 70%             200 Wh/L
Biological tolerance      Phase 3 crops         N/A             N/A
Electrolytic separation   Critical systems      95%             800 Wh/L
```

Monitoring Protocol:

· Weekly D/H ratio measurements in all water loops
· Microbial growth rate tracking as bioassay
· Seed bank maintenance with Earth-standard water

3.3 Closed-Loop Water Recycling

System Architecture:

```
Sources → Collection → Treatment → Storage → Distribution → Use
  ↑                                      ↓
  ←←←←←←←←← Recovery ←←←←←←←←←←←←←←←←←←←
```

Recovery Streams:

1. Transpiration capture: 60–70% of irrigation water
2. Condensate recovery: 90% from HVAC systems
3. SCWO output: 85–90% of input waste mass as pure water
4. Urine processing: 95% recovery via vacuum distillation
5. Hydroponic drainage: 99% recovery with ion exchange

Performance Metrics:

· Overall efficiency: >95% closed-loop
· Loss rate: <0.1% per sol (mainly airlock operations)
· Reserve capacity: 90-day supply for full population
· Quality standards: NASA potable water specifications

