8. ROBOTIC MAINTENANCE SWARM (RMS)

8.1 System Architecture

Swarm Composition (Per Standard Dome Cell):

```
Class         Quantity   Primary Function          Mass    Power
-----         --------   ----------------          ----    -----
Aero-Fly      8–12      Aerial monitoring          5 kg    200 W
Root-Bot      4–6       Soil/root care            15 kg    150 W
Bulk-Hauler   2–3       Material movement        100 kg    500 W
Specialist    1–2       SCWO maintenance          50 kg    300 W
```

Total per cell: 15–23 robots
Settlement total: 150–300 robots (10+ cells)

Communication Network:

· Primary: Mesh WiFi (5 GHz, 1 Gbps)
· Secondary: Power-line communication (backup)
· Emergency: RF (433 MHz, long-range low-bandwidth)
· Latency: <10 ms intra-dome, <100 ms inter-dome

Power System:

· Primary: Inductive charging pads (90% efficiency)
· Secondary: Swappable battery packs (4-hour runtime)
· Emergency: Supercapacitor reserve (5-minute emergency power)

8.2 Daily Operational Schedule (Martian Sol)

Shift Alpha: "Dawn" Calibration (00:00–08:00)

```
Time        Activity                          Robots Involved
----        --------                          ---------------
00:00–02:00 Ultrasonic hull survey            Aero-Fly (all)
02:00–04:00 Lighting array maintenance        Specialist + Aero-Fly
04:00–06:00 Atmospheric system calibration    All classes (coordinated)
06:00–08:00 Nutrient reservoir balancing      Root-Bot + Bulk-Hauler
```

Shift Bravo: "Growth" Management (08:00–16:00)

```
Time        Activity                          Robots Involved
----        --------                          ---------------
08:00–10:00 Plant health diagnostics          Aero-Fly (multispectral)
10:00–12:00 Precision pollination             Aero-Fly (micro-drones)
12:00–14:00 Targeted nutrient delivery        Root-Bot (per-plant)
14:00–16:00 Growth monitoring & adjustment    All (AI-coordinated)
```

Shift Charlie: "Refinery" Operations (16:00–00:00)

```
Time        Activity                          Robots Involved
----        --------                          ---------------
16:00–18:00 Harvest operations                Bulk-Hauler + Root-Bot
18:00–20:00 Waste collection to SCWO          Bulk-Hauler (primary)
20:00–22:00 Soil maintenance                  Root-Bot (tilling/inoculation)
22:00–00:00 System diagnostics & reporting    All (data aggregation)
```

8.3 Dust Storm Dormancy Protocol

Trigger Conditions:

· Solar array output <30% of nominal
· Atmospheric opacity >4.0 (tau)
· Forecast duration >48 hours

Phase 1: Preparation (6 hours pre-storm)

· Harvest all mature crops
· Charge all swarm batteries to 100%
· Fill water reservoirs to 90% capacity
· Secure all external equipment

Phase 2: Dormancy Activation (Storm onset)

· Lighting: Shift to far-red spectrum (730nm) to induce plant dormancy
· Temperature: Reduce to 15°C (lower metabolic rate)
· Irrigation: Reduce by 70% (match reduced transpiration)
· RMS activity: Reduce to 20% of normal (essential maintenance only)

Phase 3: Storm Management (During event)

· Power priority: Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Monitoring > Non-essential
· Communication: Reduced bandwidth, essential data only
· Human access: Restricted to emergency only
· Monitoring: Focus on critical parameters (pressure, temperature, O₂)

Phase 4: Recovery (Post-storm)

· Gradual ramp-up over 24–48 hours
· Spectrum return to growth-optimized settings
· Irrigation increase matched to plant recovery
· Full system diagnostic before resuming normal operations

8.4 Dust Mitigation & Maintenance

Preventive Measures:

· Positive pressure: Dome interior > exterior by 0.001 atm
· Airlock protocols: Double-door with vacuum cycle
· Filter systems: HEPA + electrostatic at all entrances
· Surface treatment: Anti-static coatings on all equipment

Robot-Specific Protection:

· Seals: Triple-lip seals on all moving joints
· Filtration: HEPA intake filters on all cooling systems
· Cleaning: Daily sonic bath (40 kHz, 5 minutes)
· Inspection: Weekly abrasion assessment on wear surfaces

Maintenance Schedule:

· Daily: Sonic cleaning, visual inspection
· Weekly: Filter replacement, joint lubrication
· Monthly: Full sensor calibration, wear part replacement
· Quarterly: Complete teardown and refurbishment

8.5 Robotic-Human Interaction Protocol (RHIP)

Motion Constraints in Human Presence:

· Maximum speed: 0.5 m/s (walking pace)
· Acceleration: <0.2 m/s² (smooth movement)
· Minimum distance: 1.5 m personal space buffer
· Path planning: Curved trajectories, no sudden movements
· Yield protocol: Robots always yield to humans

Communication Standards:

```
Status         Light Color      Sound           Meaning
------         -----------      -----           -------
Normal         Soft white       None            Standard operation
Caution        Pulsing amber    Single chime    Active task, keep clear
Warning        Solid yellow     Double chime    Minor issue, human check
Critical       Pulsing red      Triple chime    Immediate attention needed
Emergency      Flashing red     Siren           Evacuate/emergency response
```

Behavioral Protocols by Class:

· Aero-Fly: Perch at high points when humans present, avoid overhead buzzing
· Root-Bot: Operate at ground level, move aside for approaching humans
· Bulk-Hauler: Restricted to night shifts unless emergency, announces movement
· Specialist: Only enters human-occupied zones when summoned

Collaborative Interfaces:

· Augmented reality: Humans see robot intentions overlaid on reality
· Haptic feedback: Gloves provide force feedback during shared tasks
· Voice commands: Natural language for high-level instructions
· Manual override: Physical controls for emergency human direction

Emergency "Statue Mode":

· Trigger: Code Red emergency signal
· Action: All non-critical robots freeze in place
· Function: Become structural anchors/handholds
· Release: Manual reset required after emergency

